data.title: Amy Leslie - 2015-16 - Women's Tennis
data.meta_description: Amy Leslie - ACADEMICS: Major: Biochemistry and Molecular Biology Minor: Bioinformatics Academic Interests: Global Action, Filipino Student Association and A Step
data.text:
ACADEMICS:

Major: Biochemistry and Molecular Biology

Minor: Bioinformatics

Academic Interests: Global Action,

Filipino Student Association and A Step Forward, ACE (Academic Excellence Program), UCSC STEM Summer Academy. She is a member of the California Interscholastic Federation

She graduated from San Jacinto High School Class of 2015 with a GPA of 3.9.

Extracurricular activities: Marching Band, Orchestra, AVID, Interact Club, Leo Club, San Jacinto Assembly Youth Group

An interesting fact is that Amy has 309 hours of community service!

After college Amy would like to go on to Medical School and become a Surgical Oncologist.

ATHLETICS:

Leslie played tennis for four years at high school and 3 years varsity.

She was MVP for both Mountain League Pass 2014-2015 and San Jacinto High school. She also competed in Track and Field, Wrestling, Cross Country and Softball

PERSONAL:

Amy Leslie is the daughter of David and Oksana Leslie. She is the eldest of 3 daughters: Jackie, Kristina and Nikki.

She enjoys drinking teas, coffees, and Bobas, she is a musician, and also enjoys meditation and hiking.

In the community she has served groups such as Youth Sports Coaching, Hope Food Inc, the San Jacinto Assembly Youth Leadership group.

WHY UCSC:

“I choose UC Santa Cruz because I fell in love with the campus and I found a home away from home. UC Santa Cruz has one of the most beautiful campuses that is located in the middle of a forest with the view of the ocean. UCSC offered my major in Biochemistry and is well known for being a scientific research university, for which I have many opportunities to explore in research and internship positions. I'm constantly challenged in every way both academically and athletically. I love everything about UC Santa Cruz from the positive and relaxed environment to the rigorous and engaging lectures.”
